onversations about the use and meaning of color and its effects on emotions, vision, and desire. In Bright Signals Susan Murray traces these wide-ranging debates within and beyond the television industry, positioning the story of color television, which was replete with false starts, failure, and ingenuity, as central to the broader history of twentieth-century visual culture. In so doing, she shows how color television disrupted and reframed the very idea of television while it simultaneously revealed the tensions about technology's relationship to consumerism, human sight, and the natural world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aColor televisionxHistory. 0aTelevision broadcastingxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aTelevision broadcastingxTechnological innovationszUnited States. 0aTelevision broadcastingzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aKatherine Singer Kovacs Award winner. 4aSCMS award winners. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2018z978311069633240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822371700423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822371700.jpg  a978-3-11-069633-2  DUK eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles